Nothing brings people together quite like art. 
We at AD love this new show by DAG on the enigmatic figure of Tipu Sultan. An extraordinary collection of paintings, prints, maps and other objects, it recounts the visual history of the Mysore Wars between the East India Company and Tipu Sultan.

The opening night at DAG, The Claridges in New Delhi brought together a stellar line-up of people, including Dr. Shashi Tharoor, Honourable Member of Parliament, who inaugurated the historical exhibition and unveiled the accompanying book titled ‘Tipu Sultan: Image and Distance’, as well as art patrons like Kiran Nadar, Peter d'Ascoli, AD100 Sunita Kohli, Saba Ali, Muzaffar Ali Kotwara alongside Ashish Anand, MD & CEO at DAG and curator Giles Tillotson. 

Open till 31st August, 11 am – 7 pm

@dag.world 
#DAGworld @shashitharoor @kiran_nadar @smitatharoor @sunitakohli31 @peterdascoli @muzaffar.ali.kotwara @sabadelhi
#tipusultan #18thcenturyart #tigerofmysore #MysoreWars #FromTheDAGCollection #ThinkArtThinkDAG

In our next AD Visits, we head to Bengaluru, to give you a tour of Navneeth Krishna (@navneethkrishna)—a sports presenter with the Royal Challengers Bangalore (@royalchallengersbangalore)—and his partner Deepti's (@deeptikrishnan) balinese-style villa designed by Weespaces (@weespacesinteriors). The young couple's home is meticulously detailed yet unfussy. “They wanted the approach to be modern but inclusive of their heritage, inclusive of who they are,” Vinithra tells us.

The loveliest surprise is tucked away on the first floor. Originally planned as a lounge, the room was completely redesigned when Deepti put in an unconventional request for a tea room. It's “a proper Pinterest space”, as Navneeth puts it, where the star is a beautiful custom cabinet with gilt-edged drawers and striking burnt orange shelving. Stay tuned for the full tour! 

@adithi_navilekar

latestPosts.caption:
A quiet revival in Kandadu (@houseofkandadu): Presenting the July-Aug Craftsmanship issue of AD. 

In the south of India, on the Coromandel coast, is a small village called Kandadu, which has been home to well-known French embroiderer Jean-François Lesage in India. His home, (previously covered in AD), a beautiful burnt-ochre manor, is a place of community and now of revival. After a chance meeting with a young designer, Harsh Parekh—recently returned from a decade of working in haute couture in Paris—was an instant coup de foudre. The duo began a dialogue about collaborating on a brand that would pay homage to their shared love of textiles and the aesthetic of 18th-century trade between India and Europe. Bringing in another talent, Alexis de Ducla, a Frenchman passionate about craft and design—who has lived in India for two decades—created the perfect triune partnership.

“And so,” says Lesage, “House of Kandadu was born: a place, a family, a textile project.”

A niche collection of fabrics and wall coverings, House of Kandadu (@houseofkandadu) combines the techniques of block printing, kalamkari hand-painted on textiles and other specialised arts to recreate a palpable sense of imperfect, highly beautiful whimsy and decorative time travel. “We are reaching back to an age before the furnace of the Industrial Revolution changed the face of craftsmanship,” says Lesage. And Harsh Parekh elaborates: “Irregularities of the hand, the charm of natural materials, the notion of time slowing, a certain interaction with nature and the need to preserve her. These are some of the elements that inspire us about the 18th century.” And, of which, the House of Kandadu is born.

“Almost 25 years ago, along the Coromandel Coast, a local chief showed me—nestled along a quiet path lined with hundred-year-old trees—an incredible house.” So begins embroiderer Jean-François Lesage, reminiscing about the moment his South Indian home, Kandadu House (@houseofkandadu), came into his life. We sit in the balmy air of his pre-monsoon garden as he warms to his story. “This coquettish old lady seemed to be waiting for me. The owners’ family had long since left her; she had stood there proudly for 150 years, resisting the onslaught of the rains as best she could.” He talks as though remembering a great love, eyes glimmering with emotion. “She was still dignified, a little dishevelled but forgetting nothing of her past grandeur.” After two years of restoration, the burnt-ochre manor house stands now as a place of community. It is in this spirit that the Frenchman began to reflect on the future of his walled dreamland and his evolving role within it. He longed for a direction that might bring the house into a new chapter of creating and patronage. A chance meeting with a young designer, Harsh Parekh, recently returned from a decade of working in haute couture in Paris, was an instant coup de foudre. The duo began a dialogue about collaborating on a brand that would pay homage to their shared love of textiles and the aesthetic of 18th-century trade between India and Europe. Bringing in another talent, Alexis de Ducla, a Frenchman passionate about craft and design—who has lived in India for two decades—created the perfect triune partnership. “And so,” says Lesage, “House of Kandadu was born: a place, a family, a textile project.”

latestPosts.caption:
Presenting the May-June 2025 print issue of AD: One Hundred Years Of Art Deco 

In an essay on Master Sathe Bhuta, an architectural firm working in the early 20th century, Atul Kumar (@artdecomumbai) points out, “while under colonial rule, their works reflected an emerging but strong swadeshi identity, where they melded art deco with an Indian vernacular sensibility.” In Swastik Bhawan (@iamjaymmehta), the home of late Nanjibhai in Porbundar, an austere, almost Gandhian form of art deco wraps itself around the life of a traditional Gujarati family. In Shirin Bharucha’s apartment in Oval Maidan, the art deco precinct of South Bombay, the terrazzo flooring is a song. In Indore’s Manik Bagh—as seen in the Shubha & Prahlad Bubbar (@prahladbubbar) Collection—you spot the material purity and functionality of Bauhaus. And then art deco reaches the pinnacle of decadence in Jodhpur’s Umaid Bhawan (@umaidbhawanpalace). 
Finally, on the cover is Pune’s Hotel Sunderban. Housed in the historic neighbourhood of Koregaon Park, this stately bungalow was built between 1924 and 1926. Its subtle, enduring beauty made it an unexpected cover, inspite of the heavyweights in this issue. 

While we began putting together this special Art Deco issue simply for its flamboyance, we were soon face to face with the depth and diversity of how this form cross pollinated with India’s local culture. This is art deco beyond surface decoration. 

This year is the 100th anniversary of the Exposition Internationale des Arts Décoratifs et Industriels Modernes, the famous exhibition in post-war Paris which is widely regarded as marking the beginning of the style. On this occasion, we present to you the Art Deco heritage of India. 

The issue is on stands today. We hope you will pick up a copy!

On the cover: Hotel Sunderban in Pune 
Art Director: Chandini Mehta (@thebombaycat)
Photography: Sushant Deshmukh (@sushantsdeshmukh) 
Visuals Editor: Harshita Nayyar (@harshitanayyar_)
Writer: Aastha D (@aastha___d)

latestPosts.caption:
In a residential locality in southeast Bengaluru is a home with the sky at its heart and the city in its bones. It is an unusually warm day in early February when I step through its doorway and, instead of the standard configuration of rooms and walls, find myself standing in a skylit courtyard, pleasantly surprised. The structure’s boundary walls seem to shut off the noise and dust outside, and as she walks me through the space, homeowner Akhila Srinivas turns to me smiling and says, “It feels almost…monastic, no?”

This is Sri Lankan architect Palinda Kannangara’s (@palindakannangararchitects) first residential project in India, and he was determined to make it as contextual as possible—a home shaped entirely by its environment. His inspiration for it was an unusual one, Tipu Sultan’s summer palace—but how he distilled the spatial sense of a palace and infused it into a family home for four is the kind of transfiguration almost typical of his practice. 

Srinivas herself is an architect by training, but she and her husband Sharath Reddy are both entrepreneurs, each responsible for founding two of Bengaluru’s most interesting activity spaces—The Courtyard and Play Arena. The brief they shared with Kannangara was extremely detailed, but only in terms of the lifestyle and the feeling they wanted. “For instance, I explained to Palinda that I would like to be seated in an outdoor area and play board games with my daughters. Or have the kitchen spill out to a space where we could hand-pound things together,” Srinivas says. The couple had also been longtime admirers of Geoffrey Bawa, but their request for their home to have a “Sri Lankan touch”, was met with uncharacteristic intractability from the normally soft-spoken Kannangara. 

Explore the home at the link in bio

Words: @msdivyamishra 
Photography: @pempki

Two centuries ago, it was the largest private residence in Asia until fate spiralled downwards to 2004 when the World Monuments Fund listed it among the world’s 100 most endangered monuments. Such has been the dramatic journey of Patiala’s Qila Mubarak. In common with many of the subcontinent’s storied royal white elephants, the tale has been one of slow, painful decay, quickened by the vicissitudes of time and a complex webs of politics, inheritance and lack of preservation funds. However, a new chapter has unfurled thanks to visionary hotelier Priya Paul (@priyapaul) who has overseen, alongside architect Abha Narain Lambah (@abhanarainlambahassociates), an astonishing tour de force of a restoration project, transforming the former Ran Baas (@ranbaasthepalace_patiala), which once housed the royal ladies, into India’s most exciting—and much awaited—new heritage hotel. 

Having grown up in Kolkata in a family with Punjabi roots, Paul melds a keen sense of historical context with an deeply held quiet nostalgia for the lands of her ancestors so when the Punjab Bureau of Investment Promotion, an initiative by the state government, tendered part of Patiala’s fabled Qila Mubarak for a restoration project, the hotelier made a bid for what she immediately felt would be a legacy project. “We took possession in 2021, right in the middle of the pandemic aftermath,” recalls Paul. “The first step I took was to make contact with architect Abha Narain Lambah, having seen her name on documents to do with conservation work on the fort a few years earlier. She was so coherent, so knowledgeable about every stone and brick in the place, it made absolute sense to work with her, our cohesion of thought was palpable from the very start.”

Photography: @avesh.gaur

latestPosts.caption:
At the edge of the Sariska National Park—where the Aravalli hills roll out like ancient sentinels and the air is tinged with the quiet rustle of native trees—nine villas rise gently out of the wilderness. They don’t announce themselves. They don’t compete. Instead, they listen. To the landscape. To the stillness. To the rare kind of silence that only exists far from reception towers and road noise. “There was a strong sense of isolation when I first visited the site,” recalls Akshaya Mestry, founder of Studio Mestry(@studiomestry). “Not in a daunting way, but in a way that felt necessary—a place that invites you to disconnect, slow down, and recalibrate.” 

That feeling became the compass for what would become the Forest Villas at Utsav Camp (@utsavcampsariska)—a new chapter in a story that began in 2021, when Mestry was first commissioned to redesign the original structures on site. The brainchild of naturalist and hospitality veteran Luv Shekhawat, Utsav Camp was envisioned as a retreat that felt raw, untainted, and quietly luxurious. The brief this time: expand the property, deepen the experience, and build something that offered guests “refined comfort” without disturbing the landscape it sat in. 

The Sariska National Park, after all, is no ordinary backdrop. A protected reserve since the 1950s, this stretch of Rajasthan has long drawn in wildlife lovers, conservationists, and those seeking a different kind of stillness. Here, the terrain isn’t manicured—it’s wild, craggy, breathtaking. “We wanted the villas to almost emerge from that terrain,” Mestry points out, “not disrupt it, just compliment it.”

Read more at the link in bio 

Photography: @avesh.gaur 
Words: @eladas

In the semi-arid climate of Ahmedabad, with stifling summers and chilly winters, homes need to find comfort in both extremes. Enter tropical modernism: a style whose quiet elegance was born of necessity. Created in the early 20th century with the specific purpose of suiting tropical climates, the style is rooted in principles of natural light, ventilation, and locally sourced materials, as exemplified by the Aaranya home in Ahmedabad. 

Designed by interior designer Ramesh Lohar and architect Raghav Patel of R+R Architects (@rplusrarchitects), the luxury abode blurs the line between functionality with nature, inviting the outdoors into every corner of its thoughtfully composed space. “The client wanted a space that would breathe layers of elegant minimalism,” says Patel, “with sleek lines, muted tones, and the integration of nature.” And the two-storey home is exactly that. 

Natural light floods the interiors through double-height atrium skylights, while indoor greenery and expansive openings create a seamless visual connection to the outdoors. Paned with glass throughout, the home doesn’t just sit in nature—it feels intrinsically part of it.

Explore the home at the link in bio 

Photography: @ishifishy 
Words: @arianesphotos

The new deadline for submitting your entries is 30 July.

If your project transforms everyday routines into moments of calm and clarity through thoughtful yet subtle innovation, don’t miss this chance to be recognised.

How to apply:

Tap the link in our bio to fill out the entry form.

Submit at least three images of the same bathroom, taken from different angles.

You can send in multiple entries across the residential and hospitality categories, provided each submission explains how your space reflects the theme.
